Match patterns describe the values an arm accepts.

### Supported patterns

Literal patterns:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    if value is:
        1 => io.line("one")
        "ok" => io.line("text")
        true => io.line("true")
        else =>
    ;
]

Choice variants:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    if status is:
        Ready => io.line("ready")
        Status::Waiting => io.line("waiting")
    ;
]

Choice payload captures:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    if response is:
        Success => io.line("done")
        Err(message) => io.line(message)
        Pending(retry_count, message as pending_message) =>
            io.line(pending_message)
    ;
]

Option patterns:

- `none`
- literal or relational present-value patterns
- `|name|` to capture any present value

General capture:

A bare pattern name that is not a known choice variant binds the complete
scrutinee value for that arm.

Relational patterns:

```text
< value
<= value
> value
>= value
```

Relational patterns support `Int`, `Float`, `Char` and `String`. String ordering
is backend-defined in the current Alpha surface.

### Choice payload captures

- Payload captures must list every declared field.
- Captures stay in declaration order.
- The source name before `as` must exactly match the declared field name.
- `as local_name` changes only the arm-local binding.
- Duplicate local bindings are invalid.
- Wildcard payload captures are not supported.
- Named assignment syntax such as `Err(message = text)` is not payload-pattern syntax.
- Nested payload patterns are deferred.

### Exhaustiveness

- A non-choice full match requires `else =>`.
- A choice match may omit `else =>` only when every variant is covered.
- Any guarded choice arm requires `else =>`.
- The same choice variant cannot be matched more than once.
- Payload exhaustiveness is tag-level. One valid payload capture arm covers every value of that variant.
- A statement match may use bodyless `else =>`.
- A value-producing match must produce the required values on every selected path.

An unconditional general capture covers every remaining value. A later arm or
default is unreachable.

Capture bindings are arm-local and follow the no-shadowing rule.
